         <abstract>
            <p>Using the theory of uniform distribution modulo one, it is shown that under certain conditions on the real-valued functions $\alpha(x)$ and $g(x)$ on \lbrack 0, 1 \rbrack$, $$h \sum^{\lbrack h^{-1} \rbrack}_{\gamma = 1} \{h^{-1} \alpha(\gamma h)\}^m g(\gamma h) = (m + 1)^{-1} \int^1_0 g(x) dx + O\bigg(h^{1/3} \log \frac{1}{h}\bigg) \text{as} h \rightarrow 0 +,$$ where $m &gt; 0$ and $\{x\}$ denotes the fractional part of $x$. The conditions are as follows: $\alpha''(x)$ exists for all but finitely many points in $\lbrack 0, 1 \rbrack$, changes sign at most finitely often, and is bounded away in absolute value from both 0 and $\infty$, whereas $g(x)$ is of bounded variation on $\lbrack 0, 1 \rbrack$. Also, under these conditions on $\alpha(x)$, $$h \sum^{\lbrack h^{-1} \rbrack}_{\gamma = 1} \{h^{-1} \alpha(\gamma h)\}^m = (m + 1)^{-1} + O(h^{1/3}) \text{as} h \rightarrow 0+.$$ These results, which are, in fact, deduced from somewhat more general propositions, answer questions of Feldstein connected with discretization methods for differential equations.</p>
          </abstract>
